article.description: The Indiana Fever have to be pleased with the offseason acquisition of Kelly Miller.
article.headline: Indiana opens season on positive note
article.linkText: Fever nip Liberty behind Miller's 18 points
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- When New York's defense clamped down on
All-Star forward Tamika Catchings, newcomer Kelly Miller stepped up
for Indiana.


Miller, acquired in an offseason trade from Charlotte, scored 18
points in her debut with Indiana on Friday night, leading the Fever
to a 69-67 victory over the Liberty in the opener for both teams.

"When someone is out or struggling, someone else has got to
pick it up," said Miller, who shot 5-for-6 in the first half after
barely averaging four points in her first three WNBA seasons. "We
had to do that tonight. We have a lot of scoring threats. That's
what's going to make us dangerous."

The Liberty held Catchings to 4-for-12 shooting and 14 points,
five below her career average.

"Having Kelly out on the court makes it much easier for me,"
Catchings said. "People have to respect her. If you drive and
she's open and you kick it to her, you know the ball's going in."

The teams were tied 36-all at halftime, but the Fever took
control by holding the Liberty scoreless for nearly five minutes
while scoring 10 points to make it 52-40 with 13:55 remaining.

Kristen Rasmussen made two free throws with 10.4 seconds
remaining to give the Fever a 69-64 lead before the Liberty's
Crystal Robinson made a 3-pointer at the buzzer.

First-year Fever coach Brian Winters liked his team's balance.

"I looked at the stat sheet at the half, and Tamika was
1-for-7. But hey, we were tied," Winters said. "It's nice you can
get some points from other places. Kelly Miller played a nice
game."

The Fever forced 18 turnovers and, while outrebounded 38-36 for
the game, grabbed 15 on the offensive boards, including 12 after
the break. Indiana's Natalie Williams had 12 rebounds to go with
her 11 points.

"In the second half, we gave too many offensive rebounds,
compared to three in the first half," Liberty coach Richie Adubato
said. "We had too many turnovers.

"It was a good game, but at times, we broke down and didn't
execute," Adubato said.

Robinson and Vickie Johnson scored 16 points each for New York.
